entries.title: South Africa to Hold Naval Drill With Russia and China Amid Ukraine War
entries.description: The 10-day naval exercises are a show of diplomatic independence for South Africa, which is part of an alliance with Brazil, Russia, India and China — known as BRICS.

entries.title: Trump’s Interior Secretary Didn’t Violate Ethics Rules, Watchdog Finds
entries.description: An inspector general’s report found no evidence that David Bernhardt had improperly favored a group that once employed him as a lobbyist.

entries.title: The Debate Over Sending Tanks to Ukraine
entries.description: Western nations are amping up offensive military power for Ukraine in almost every category except the one Kyiv says it needs the most. Here’s why.

entries.title: What Is the Leopard 2 Tank, and How Could It Help Ukraine?
entries.description: One of the world’s leading battle tanks, the German-made Leopard 2 has sophisticated targeting capabilities, even in rough terrain.

entries.title: A Bus Driver’s Ode to His Job Is a Surprise Music Video Hit
entries.description: The video features Ranjit Singh Veer driving his bus in the West Midlands of Britain and leading a Punjabi bhangra dance crew. It has drawn tens of thousands of views in the last week.

entries.title: A Secret Room and a Comfortable Life: A Mobster’s Years on the Run
entries.description: Since the arrest earlier this week of Matteo Messina Denaro, a picture of his time on the lam is starting to take shape.

entries.title: Can Art Ever Be Innocent?
entries.description: A riveting show at the Metropolitan Museum surveys the complicated art of the ancient Maya, in which beauty and brutality are surreally entangled.

entries.title: India’s Love Story With ‘D.D.L.J’ Is Still Strong After 27 Years
entries.description: ‘D.D.L.J.,’ which a Mumbai theater has shown nearly every day since 1995, encapsulates a society in churn, with the choices afforded by economic opportunity clashing with tradition.

entries.title: Ukraine Will Investigate the Cause of a Deadly Helicopter Crash
entries.description: The helicopter came down near a kindergarten and a residential building outside Kyiv, killing the interior minister and others and causing severe damage.

entries.title: Stampede Outside Soccer Stadium in Iraq Leaves at Least One Dead
entries.description: Thousands of fans thronged an arena in the southern city of Basra for a match involving the national team. Many were angry to discover that they had been sold fake tickets, a witness said.

entries.title: Workers in France Strike Over Macron’s Plan to Raise Retirement Age
entries.description: Labor unions, opposed to government plans to raise the legal age of retirement, want a show of strength. President Emmanuel Macron is hoping to forge ahead despite the wave of discontent.

entries.title: Israel’s Judicial Standoff Deepens as Netanyahu Delays Firing Minister
entries.description: The Israeli prime minister has yet to uphold a decision by the Supreme Court that a key government minister convicted of tax fraud should be dismissed.

entries.title: How Covid Played a Role in Jacinda Ardern’s Resignation
entries.description: In a part of the world where coronavirus restrictions lingered, Jacinda Ardern struggled to get beyond her association with pandemic policy.

entries.title: Betting on Gotham
entries.description: The pandemic may finally have cleared the way for a casino in New York City.

entries.title: On These Small Islands, Medical Care Arrives One Ship at a Time
entries.description: Much of rural South Korea has seen its population rapidly decline and age. For some communities off the coast, doctors traveling by boat have become a lifeline for the old and sick.

entries.title: Whitney Curator Marcela Guerrero Leads the Way on Latino Art
entries.description: In her five years at the museum, Marcela Guerrero has helped broaden the scope of artists and audiences as the Hispanic population continues to grow and museums try to reflect more diverse audiences.

entries.title: How Do California’s Storms Weigh In Compared With History’s Big Ones?
entries.description: Rain and snowfall this season are above average, but the state has seen some wild weather in past years.

entries.title: Could Air Someday Power Your Flight? Airlines Are Betting on It.
entries.description: New technologies, including one fuel extracted from the atmosphere itself, could make flying more sustainable. But the challenges are many and the timeline is uncertain.

entries.title: Jacinda Ardern’s Career
entries.description: New Zealand’s outgoing prime minister won global fame with youthful charisma and a frank, compassionate leadership style that carried her through crisis.

entries.title: Death of Zelensky Aide Leaves Void in Leadership Team
entries.description: Ukraine is rushing to prepare for a possible renewed Russian assault without the official who oversaw the country’s domestic security.

entries.title: Tunisian Cave Village Empties Out in Face of Drought and Modernity’s Draw
entries.description: For 1,000 years, homes dug into a desert cliff have sheltered olive farmers and sheep herders from summer heat and winter cold. But an exodus threatens its future. “We are left alone here.”

entries.title: Your Thursday Briefing
entries.description: A helicopter crash in Ukraine and the resignation of Jacinda Ardern.

entries.title: Helicopter Crash Kills Ukrainian Minister in Blow to Wartime Leadership
entries.description: The crash in a suburb of Kyiv killed at least 14 people, officials said, including the interior minister, a top adviser to President Volodymyr Zelensky, who oversaw Ukraine’s domestic security.

entries.title: Jacinda Ardern to Step Down as New Zealand’s Prime Minister, She Says
entries.description: The prime minister said she would step down on Feb. 7.
